Corporate Mundo and Brolaf both have new voice lines, new models, and modified particles, and the 1820 price tag is still fairly justified since most skins don't get the full VO treatment (plus they're the most recent of this batch).
Gentleman Cho'Gath and Nunu Bot both have brand new voice lines, which when they were released was completely unique to skins at their time, gaining them the Legendary slot. The rest are some of *the* original legendary skins when they were still fleshing out the skin system, so things like minor remodels (Tibbers with rabbit ears, Magnificent TF, Red Baron plane, Ice Toboggan Luge, Alien head and turrets) and special particle effects (Firefighter's water, Lion Dance's fireworks) were enough to earn them an 1820 price tag. Since those days, skin quality has vastly increased due to Riot's technology, their increased personnel, and their better funding, so naturally, older skins won't seem up to par anymore. That being said, most of the very antiquated skins that do not have anything fancier than remodels are retired.
 You must understand that when these skins were first coming out, a "skin" was usually a very light retexture of a champion, so anything more required a lot more effort on a game company that was still up and coming. Furthermore, Riot's stance on skin pricing is generally set in stone. They don't permanently lower skin prices because it devalues the skin for players who back then may have purchased it at full price. So while it sucks that you don't get as much bang for your buck with these skins, they are the epitome of vintage and most are super rare on account of being vaulted. The only ways to get most of these skins that are vaulted is either through a very special event that releases them (champ relaunch, holiday, legacy event), mystery gifting, or Hextech Crafting.

